{
  "texts": [
    "It determines how much the model's parameters should be adjusted based on the computed gradients.",
    "A smaller learning rate means that the model parameters will be updated more slowly and cautiously, which can help prevent overshooting the optimal values.",
    "However, it also means that the optimization process may take longer to converge.",
    "On the other hand, a larger learning rate means that the model parameters will be updated more aggressively, which can result in faster convergence but may also cause the optimizer to overshoot the optimal values.",
    "Evaluating the model's performance is a crucial aspect of this study, encompassing assessments for both non-fine-tuned models and at each epoch during the finetuning process."
  ]
}